+{"id":"frankenpandas-0xxdr","title":"fd90.103: README claims 10 null-skipping aggregation primitives but fp-types exposes 19 (sem/ptp/skew/kurt/any/all/quantile/argmax/argmin missing)","description":"fd90.74-102 README audit. Line 771 says 'The fp-types crate provides 10 null-skipping aggregation primitives that underpin all statistical operations' and lists 10 nan* functions: nansum, nanmean, nancount, nanmin, nanmax, nanmedian, nanvar, nanstd, nanprod, nannunique. But crates/fp-types/src/lib.rs actually exposes 23 nan* public functions:

Scalar reductions (19, all fit 'aggregation primitive' framing):
  nansum, nanmean, nancount, nanmin, nanmax, nanmedian,
  nanvar, nanstd, nanprod, nannunique,
  nanany, nanall, nansem, nanptp, nanskew, nankurt,
  nanquantile, nanargmax, nanargmin

Cumulative transforms (4, return Vec<Scalar> — out of 'aggregation' scope):
  nancumsum, nancumprod, nancummax, nancummin

The README's '10 primitives' is a roughly half-count understatement. Fix: bump 10 → 19 (or use '20+' as a defensible lower bound) and add the 9 missing reductions to the code block (any/all, sem/ptp/skew/kurt, quantile, argmax/argmin) so the listed examples back the headline number. Pure README change.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-26T10:04:36.235232515Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T10:05:58.471831386Z","closed_at":"2026-04-26T10:05:58.469158411Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"frankenpandas-0yz7","title":"[REALITY-CHECK HIGH] MultiIndex marked Yes-foundation but row MultiIndex absent","description":"README capability table: MultiIndex Yes (foundation) — note the foundation qualifier. Reality: br-r4au tried to ship row MultiIndex emission for grouped rolling/resample by encoding tuples as flat Utf8 strings (a, 2024-01) because real row MultiIndex is not wired through DataFrame; br-ch4o reverted that workaround back to group-key column + bucket-only flat index. Concrete absences: (1) DataFrame::index returns Index<IndexLabel> not MultiIndex<Vec<IndexLabel>>; (2) groupby([k1,k2]).sum output uses string-flattened keys like s:a|i:1 (per FP-P2C-005, FP-P2C-011) not real (k1, k2) tuples; (3) no .loc[(a, 1)] tuple-key indexing; (4) stack/unstack and reset_index for MultiIndex frames are scaffolded but not behaviorally complete. Suggested: split the README MultiIndex row into Column MultiIndex (Yes-foundation) and Row MultiIndex (No), file an epic for genuine row MultiIndex.","notes":"cc-pandas triage 2026-04-22 (commit 14a74c6): split the conflated 'MultiIndex | Yes (foundation)' capability table row into Row MultiIndex (Scaffolded) and Column MultiIndex (Yes-foundation), matching the actual in-tree reality after br-ch4o reverted br-r4au's tuple-emission attempt. MultiIndex section prose (README.md:396) now names the flattening mechanism ('a|1' separator via set_index_multi) and enumerates the specific scaffolded surfaces (tuple .loc, row-MultiIndex groupby output, stack/unstack, reset_index round-trip) with cross-references to the capability table and Limitations. Existing Limitations entry (README.md:1372) already honest; kept. Follow-up epic filed as br-frankenpandas-1zzp covering the full row-axis integration work (6 slices: DataFrame row-axis type, multi-key GroupBy output, tuple indexing, reshape round-trips, IO multi-row index block, live-oracle coverage).","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","assignee":"cc-pandas","created_at":"2026-04-22T09:23:14.932108470Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-22T11:41:38.676116789Z","closed_at":"2026-04-22T11:41:38.673534621Z","closed_by_session":"cc-pandas-0yz7","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
